        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The CO emission will be recorded using three 58.594 MHz wide bands which deliver a velocity 
resolution of about 40 m/s after Hanning smoothing. The data will be resampled at the velocity 
resolution of 50 m/s required to achive our scince goal, as discussed in the scientific justification.  The fourth band is set to TDM mode for continuum observations. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>In resubmitting this proposal for Cycle 3, we request the same angular resolution required for cycle 2 observations, namely 0.23 arcsec, which can be achieved is the C36-5 array configuration. 
This angular resolution resolve the mideplane CO snowline in more than 100 resolution elements, which is key to accurately measure the spatial variations of the line width. The maximum angular
scale that is sampled in the C36-5 configuration at Band 6 is 3.4" which is larger than the CO snow line. Although not necessary to achieve the science goal of the proposed research, we plan to combine Cycle 3 data with the available observations from Science verification to recover the 
disk emission on scales larger than 3.4"</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Based on the simulation shown in Figure 2, we request a rms noise of 4 mJy/beam in a 50 m/s wide channel to detect the C18O emission with a peak signal-to-noise ratio &gt; 10 in most of the spectral channels across the CO line. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The high data rate is required to achive the velocity resolution of 50 m/s necessary to measure 
the turbulent velocity in the HD163296 disk. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_HIGH_DATA_RATE</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
    </prj:ScienceGoal>
